author: Marc Ramirez
title: Newspaper runs Alec Baldwin photo instead of Donald Trump, Twitter has a ball
text:
El Nacional, via Huffington Post Newspaper runs Alec Baldwin photo instead of Donald Trump, Twitter has a ball Filed under Donald Trump at 36 min ago Get Daily Dallas News Headlines Sign Up Get Unlimited Digital Access Your first month is less than a dollar. $0.99 for first 4 weeks Subscribe Now 
Just how good is actor Alec Baldwin's Donald Trump impression? A Dominican Republic newspaper apparently couldn't tell the difference. 
As several news outlets have observed, El Nacional ran a story Friday about the U.S. President and his positions on Israeli settlements. There, on the right, was a photo of serious-faced Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu. Dominican newspaper uses picture of Alex Baldwin instead of president Trump. pic.twitter.com/exxsAufnrd — You Had One Job (@_youhadonejob1) February 11, 2017 
On the left? An Associated Press image of a purse-lipped Baldwin in full resting fish-face, from NBC's Saturday Night Live , where he has been regularly playing the role, to the President's apparent exasperation. Just tried watching Saturday Night Live - unwatchable! Totally biased, not funny and the Baldwin impersonation just can't get any worse. Sad — Donald J. Trump (@realDonaldTrump) December 4, 2016 
Coincidentally, Baldwin will be hosting this weekend's show. 
The newspaper published a correction soon thereafter, but not before the Twittersphere had gotten its hands all over it, mocking "that awkward moment when" the error that was bound to happen finally happened. Unbelievable! Dominican newspaper @ElNacional_RD uses wrong picture of Trump. Source: https://t.co/iqljfAAVVH #SNL pic.twitter.com/ENZ7HeKU6V — Pradiip Alvarez (@GlobalVzla) February 11, 2017 
"Dear El Nacional," one Twitter user posted, "Alec Baldwin will be pleased as punch. But let's hope the Dominican Republic isn't added to Trump's banned countries list." 
London's The Independent noted that the El Nacional article "was not intended to be satirical or tongue-in-cheek, which makes the entire error more hilarious." 
Whether any publication will accidentally use a photo of Melissa McCarthy impersonating Sean Spicer instead of the actual White House press secretary remains to be seen. View Comments
